</div></div></div>";s:14:"date_timestamp";i:1521160326;}i:9;a:8:{s:5:"title";s:58:"Study shows gully wildlife refuges have high bushfire risk";s:4:"link";s:98:"http://newsroom.uts.edu.au/news/2018/02/study-shows-gully-wildlife-refuges-have-high-bushfire-risk";s:11:"description";s:5482:"<div class="slick slick--skin--fullwidth slick--optionset--article unslick" id="slick-node-32717-article-2016-field-feature-image-9">
  
                      <div class="slide__media">      <div class="slick-media media media--image">
<img src="http://newsroom.uts.edu.au/sites/default/files/styles/wide_landscape/public/images/article_feature/hazard-reduction-Faulconbridge-17-2015-%28003%29.jpg?itok=NWx1oXr9" width="980" height="560" alt="More frequent and intense bushfires are predicted for south-eastern Australia. Picture by Dr Brad Murray" title="More frequent and intense bushfires are predicted for south-eastern Australia. Picture by Dr Brad Murray" /></div>
            </div>
              <div class="slide__constrained">        <div class="slide__caption">
          
                      
                          <h2 class="slide__title">More frequent and intense bushfires are predicted for south-eastern Australia. Picture by Dr Brad Murray</h2>
            
            
            
            
                              </div>
        </div>                      
  </div>
<div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p class="uts-lead">The first evidence showing important landscape differences in the flammability of plant leaves, as fuels available for bushfires, indicates that gully plant communities are likely to be at increased risk under climate change and increasing bushfire frequency and intensity.</p>
<p>Research from the University of Technology Sydney (UTS) shows that plant communities in gullies are much more flammable than plant communities on ridge-tops.</p>
<p>Ecologist, and lead investigator of the study, <a href="https://www.uts.edu.au/staff/brad.murray">Dr Brad Murray</a> says that the results of the research into plant flammability are of serious concern, because ?all sorts of animals have normally used gullies as refuges during bushfires.?</p>
<p>How environmentally selected variation in leaf traits, such as leaf area (LA) and leaf mass per area (LMA), drives variation in leaf flammability at landscape scales has remained largely unknown until now. The study compares leaf traits and flammability characteristics between species of sheltered forest vegetation (low light, moist habitat) and plant species of exposed woodland vegetation (high light, dry habitat) in a fire-prone landscape of south-eastern Australia.<br />
 <br />
The researchers found that leaves of sheltered forest species were significantly more flammable due to both higher ignitibility and combustibility compared with exposed woodland species.</p>
<p>?These significant differences [in leaf ignitibility and combustibility] are reinforced by sheltered forest species having leaves with significantly larger LA and lower LMA compared with exposed woodland species,? says Daniel Krix, UTS School of Life Sciences PhD student and lead author of the study published in <a href="http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/ecs2.2093/pdf">Ecosphere</a>.</p>
<p>Sheltered forest habitat tends to burn less frequently and less intensely than exposed woodland, however, projected changes to climate will allow wildfires to overcome the once protective nature of gully topography, the researchers say.</p>
<p>?Wildfire frequency and intensity is projected to increase which means that higher leaf flammability in sheltered forest species has the potential to exacerbate the effects of changing weather conditions to place sheltered forest habitat, their plants and their animals, at even higher risk of catastrophic wildfire,? Dr Murray says.</p>
<p>?If the gullies are becoming more at risk of going up in huge fires, then where will the animals go?? he says.</p>
</div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-summary field-type-text-long field-label-above"><div class="field-label">In summary:&nbsp;</div><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><ul><li>Scientists have found that plant communities in gullies, where animals typically take shelter during bushfires, are potentially more flammable than exposed woodlands</li>
<li>With frequent, more intense bushfires predicted for south-eastern Australia, it's feared these biodiverse wildlife refuges are now at risk</li>
</ul></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-partners field-type-link-field field-label-above"><div class="field-label">This research is funded by:&nbsp;</div><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><a href="https://www.education.gov.au/research-training-program">Australian Government Research Training Program</a></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-themes field-type-taxonomy-term-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><a href="/themes/health-and-science">Health and Science</a></div><div class="field-item odd"><a href="/themes/social-justice-and-sustainability">Social Justice and Sustainability</a></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-source field-type-taxonomy-term-reference field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even">The Newsroom</div></div></div><div class="field field-name-field-new-byline field-type-link-field field-label-above"><div class="field-label">Byline:&nbsp;</div><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><a href="https://www.uts.edu.au/staff/marea.martlew">Marea Martlew</a></div></div></div>";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Tue, 20 Feb 2018 02:46:05 +0000";s:4:"guid";s:35:"32717 at http://newsroom.uts.edu.au";s:8:"comments";s:107:"http://newsroom.uts.edu.au/news/2018/02/study-shows-gully-wildlife-refuges-have-high-bushfire-risk#comments";s:7:"summary";s:5482:"<div class="slick slick--skin--fullwidth slick--optionset--article unslick" id="slick-node-32717-article-2016-field-feature-image-9">
  
                      <div class="slide__media">      <div class="slick-media media media--image">
<img src="http://newsroom.uts.edu.au/sites/default/files/styles/wide_landscape/public/images/article_feature/hazard-reduction-Faulconbridge-17-2015-%28003%29.jpg?itok=NWx1oXr9" width="980" height="560" alt="More frequent and intense bushfires are predicted for south-eastern Australia. Picture by Dr Brad Murray" title="More frequent and intense bushfires are predicted for south-eastern Australia. Picture by Dr Brad Murray" /></div>
            </div>
              <div class="slide__constrained">        <div class="slide__caption">
          
                      
                          <h2 class="slide__title">More frequent and intense bushfires are predicted for south-eastern Australia. Picture by Dr Brad Murray</h2>
            
            
            
            
                              </div>
        </div>                      
  </div>
<div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p class="uts-lead">The first evidence showing important landscape differences in the flammability of plant leaves, as fuels available for bushfires, indicates that gully plant communities are likely to be at increased risk under climate change and increasing bushfire frequency and intensity.</p>
